'''Adrena Adrena''' is a collaboration between visual artist '''Daisy Dickinson''' and drummer '''E-Da Kazuhisa'''.

Kazuhisa was previously the drummer of the Japanese noise band [[Boredoms]] and is currently with the British electronic/post-rock band [[Seefeel]]. The duo cut a raw blend of drums, noise and organic visual work, featuring in their performances an eight-foot white sphere that hangs above Kazuhisa’s drum kit and which Dickinson maps videos on to; her work was described by William Barns-Graham of Fluid Radio as ‘cosmological and transcendental, drawing attention to the wonder of the earth and our sensuality on it’.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fluid-radio.co.uk/2017/01/audio-visual-session-sculpture-adrena-adrena-ovo/|title=Live Session: Sculpture, Adrena Adrena & OvO|date=2017-01-05|work=Fluid Radio|access-date=2017-07-29|language=en-GB}}</ref>

Their debut was at the International Festival of Projections in early 2016, and they have since performed at the [[End of the Road Festival]], Supernormal Festival, Fort Process Festival, Zorofest in [[Leipzig]], Splice Festival and other shows across the UK and Europe with [[Acid Mothers Temple]] and members of [[Wire (band)|Wire]] and [[Bo Ningen]].

In 2016, the pair completed a short film, ''Man on the Hill'', which features Kazuhisa playing drums on fire in the mountains. The film has since been featured on the [[British Council]] Film website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/man-on-the-hill|title=British Council Film: Man on the Hill|last=Film|first=British Council|website=film.britishcouncil.org|access-date=2016-12-14}}</ref> In 2016 the film was nominated for the [[BFI London Film Festival]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/lff/Online/default.asp?BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::permalink=talesofmysteryandimagination|title=Buy cinema tickets for Tales of Mystery and Imagination {{!}} BFI London Film Festival 2016|website=whatson.bfi.org.uk|access-date=2016-12-14}}</ref> the [[Encounters Short Film and Animation Festival]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://encounters-festival.org.uk/events/lets-dance/|title=Let's Dance - MUSIC VIDEOS & DANCE FILMS - Encounters Film Festival|newspaper=Encounters Film Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-14}}</ref> the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] qualifying Aesthetica Short Film Festival, [http://www.londonexperimentalfilmfestival.com The London Experimental Film Festival], [http://www.vienna-film-festival.com Vienna Independent Short Film Festival] and the [http://shortfilms.org.uk London Short Film Festival].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shortfilms.org.uk/events/2017-01-08-new-shorts-experiments-leftfield-luscious|title=NEW SHORTS: Experiments: Leftfield + Luscious|website=shortfilms.org.uk|access-date=2016-12-14}}</ref> The film was also featured in [[I-D|i-D Magazine]] Japan, naming Dickinson as one of the five most watched filmmakers in Japan at the time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://i-d.vice.com/jp/article/5-most-watched-film-maker-from-japan|title=ロンドンで活躍する5組の日本人映像作家 |work=i-D|access-date=2017-07-29|language=en}}</ref>

After completing ''Man on the Hill,'' they went on to release their first music video ''Toy'', premiering on the Ransom Note in 2017<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theransomnote.com/music/premieres-exclusive-streams/first-view-adrena-adrena-toy/|title=First View: Adrena Adrena - Toy|access-date=2017-07-29}}</ref> and following that appeared at various shows across the UK and Europe alongside the likes of [[Damo Suzuki]] ([[Can (band)|Can]]) and [[Immersion (musicians)|Immersion]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/22413-immersion-adrena-adrena-karel-doing-audio-visual-night-2|title=The Quietus {{!}} News {{!}} Immersion & More For Audio Visual Night #2|work=The Quietus|access-date=2017-07-29}}</ref> and [[Snapped Ankles]], where their performance was described by [[Loud and Quiet]] as "it looked like a planet, a marble, the inside of a brain, or was filled by trapped insects and humans. The effect was transfixing, and comes highly recommended."<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.loudandquiet.com/short/snapped-ankles-was-only-gig-in-london-men-dressed-as-trees/|title=Snapped Ankles was the only gig happening in London last night where four people dressed as trees played in a warehouse|work=Loud And Quiet|access-date=2017-07-29|language=en-US}}</ref>

They are featured as one of [[Cafe Oto]]'s artists, accompanied by a review from Gavin Burrows of the blog Lucid Frenzy which reads "The centre of the stage was taken up by projections which, always simple and often semi-abstract, never stole the limelight from the music. It was more like watching a trio, just one at work on different senses to the others. Pretty soon you weren't taking in the sights and sounds as separate elements at all, but hand been induced into a kind of synaesthesia. And if that seems like we're reverting to Sixties terminology like 'trip' we might as well go with it.... it felt like a trip (man), like being taken through some other reality then dumped back in ours at the end." <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cafeoto.co.uk/artists/adrena-adrena/|title=Adrena Adrena  ← People ← Cafe OTO|website=www.cafeoto.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-07-29}}</ref>

In January 2018 they performed [http://shortfilms.org.uk/events/2018-01-12-opening-night-movements-of-a-nebulous-dawn 'Movements of a Nebulous Dawn'] for the opening night of the [[London Short Film Festival]] at the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ica.art/whats-on/lsff-movements-nebulous-dawn|title=LSFF: Movements of a Nebulous Dawn|website=www.ica.art|language=en|access-date=2018-01-14}}</ref> London, presenting a one-off audiovisual collaboration with a 360-degree nebulous orb defying the conventions of theatrical presentation as musicians performed in-the-round beneath multiple circular projections created by Dickinson. The improvised live set curated by Adrena Adrena featured guest musicians [[Damo Suzuki]] ([[Can (band)|Can]]), [[Geraldine Swayne]] ([[Faust (band)|Faust]]), [[Colin Newman]] ([[Wire (band)|Wire]]), [[Malka Spigel]] ([[Minimal Compact]]) and Kenichi Iwasa ([[Krautrock Karaoke]]).

