==History== Under [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman rule]], there were no laws on prostitution.<ref name="city">{{cite book|last1=García|first1=Magaly Rodríguez|last2=van Voss|first2=Lex Heerma|last3=Nederveen Meerkerk|first3=Elise van|title=Selling Sex in the City: A Global History of Prostitution, 1600s-2000s|date=21 Sep 2017|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-9004346246|pages=337–338}}</ref>
After coming under [[United Kingdom|British]] control during [[WW1]], the attitude of the Authorities towards prostitution reflected those of Britain. Ordinances were issued in 1925 (under [[High Commissioner]] [[Herbert Samuel, 1st Viscount Samuel|Herbert Samuel]]) and 1927 (under [[Herbert Plumer, 1st Viscount Plumer|Herbert Plumer]] introduced laws on prostitution similar to those in Britain. Soliciting, living off the earnings of prostitutes and the keeping of brothels were outlawed.<ref name="city" />
There is evidence that in [[WW2]], military authorities regulated brothels for soldiers, including medical examinations.<ref name="city" />
